75
00:04:09.360 --> 00:04:13.000
So as a clinician and many of my colleagues who are in the

76
00:04:13.040 --> 00:04:16.680
room are engaged in cancer predisposition testing and

77
00:04:16.780 --> 00:04:20.340
clinical care for children, we often question, should

78
00:04:20.380 --> 00:04:24.120
newborn screening include testing for cancer

79
00:04:24.220 --> 00:04:27.660
predisposition? And if so, which genes, what

80
00:04:27.680 --> 00:04:31.640
technology in order to implement this in a cost-effective manner?

81
00:04:32.140 --> 00:04:34.860
And if not, which is the current situation, why not?

82
00:04:35.920 --> 00:04:39.820
So just to frame a case, and this is from my colleague Lisa Diller,

83
00:04:39.880 --> 00:04:42.940
who also shared some of her unpublished data for this talk.

84
00:04:43.560 --> 00:04:46.920
This is a boy diagnosed at 18 months with bilateral

85
00:04:46.960 --> 00:04:50.640
retinoblastoma, underwent intensive treatment, including

86
00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:54.400
bilateral enucleations, and was identified to have an RB1

87
00:04:54.500 --> 00:04:58.130
pathogenic variant. His sister was then tested as a

88
00:04:58.200 --> 00:05:01.640
newborn. She was able to have local therapy and

89
00:05:01.740 --> 00:05:03.200
preserve normal vision.

90
00:05:05.200 --> 00:05:05.500
Whoop.

91
00:05:07.680 --> 00:05:09.980
And is the animation not going to work? Okay.

92
00:05:10.180 --> 00:05:13.820
And her mother asked, "Why don't you test everyone for this

93
00:05:13.860 --> 00:05:17.820
disease when they are born?" And that's a question we frequently get

94
00:05:17.900 --> 00:05:19.640
in the children's cancer centers.

95
00:05:20.660 --> 00:05:24.020
So let's talk a little bit about newborn screening because this audience probably

96
00:05:24.120 --> 00:05:26.500
isn't that familiar. It is a process.

97
00:05:26.800 --> 00:05:29.840
Every baby in the United States is approached.

98
00:05:29.920 --> 00:05:33.520
Families are informed, but consent is not required because it's

99
00:05:33.580 --> 00:05:37.280
considered a public health effort, and we get a quality

100
00:05:37.420 --> 00:05:41.300
heel stick on a Guthrie card between 24 and 48 hours

101
00:05:41.340 --> 00:05:41.880
of life.

102
00:05:42.750 --> 00:05:45.820
The hospitals send these daily to,

103
00:05:46.660 --> 00:05:50.250
in the United States, these are state labs, in other countries, they're sometimes

104
00:05:50.280 --> 00:05:53.980
national labs, and the testing is performed there

105
00:05:54.140 --> 00:05:57.560
with lots of need for quality control and data integrity.

106
00:05:58.400 --> 00:06:02.340
If a child is positive, there's another whole team that actually

107
00:06:02.380 --> 00:06:06.220
reaches out. They have to find the baby, because for many of these disorders,

108
00:06:06.520 --> 00:06:08.540
you have to do treatment immediately,

109
00:06:09.520 --> 00:06:13.312
or there's long-term surveillance.So what is the

110
00:06:13.332 --> 00:06:15.992
criteria to be included in newborn screening?

111
00:06:16.132 --> 00:06:19.592
And that comes originally from a paper back in 1968.

112
00:06:19.972 --> 00:06:22.452
It needs to be a clinically important condition.

113
00:06:22.772 --> 00:06:25.352
There has to be a screening test that can be done.

114
00:06:25.892 --> 00:06:29.392
There need to be facilities at hospitals to diagnose and treat the

115
00:06:29.432 --> 00:06:33.232
disorder. The treatment has to be acceptable to the

116
00:06:33.272 --> 00:06:37.152
medical community, and it has to be a condition you can't otherwise

117
00:06:37.192 --> 00:06:41.002
recognize based on physical features or clinical

118
00:06:41.232 --> 00:06:45.192
presentation. You do have to know something about the natural history

119
00:06:45.232 --> 00:06:48.992
of the disorder if a test is positive, and it has to be

120
00:06:49.032 --> 00:06:52.692
cost effective in some way to diagnose and treat.

121
00:06:52.752 --> 00:06:56.632
So what do we currently do? In most states, we test between 50

122
00:06:56.672 --> 00:06:58.361
to 60 different conditions,

123
00:06:59.432 --> 00:07:02.752
often done by tandem mass spec for metabolic disorders.

124
00:07:02.972 --> 00:07:06.692
Some are done by ELISA assays. We now do Treg circles for

125
00:07:06.772 --> 00:07:10.472
SCID, and there's deletion duplication analysis for

126
00:07:10.712 --> 00:07:13.852
SMA. There are almost no primary

127
00:07:14.012 --> 00:07:17.871
sequence-based diagnostic tests being done, and there's no

128
00:07:17.952 --> 00:07:19.591
cancer risk testing at all.

129
00:07:21.112 --> 00:07:25.042
So if we think about childhood cancer, and I'm just quoting some of my own work,

130
00:07:25.132 --> 00:07:28.472
this has been done by many different groups.

131
00:07:28.792 --> 00:07:32.732
This is our data from a thousand patients prospectively

132
00:07:32.752 --> 00:07:36.592
enrolled in with solid tumors in exome sequencing

133
00:07:36.602 --> 00:07:40.252
trials. And overall, 10 to 12% of these

134
00:07:40.292 --> 00:07:44.232
children carry a pathogenic or likely pathogenic variant in a cancer

135
00:07:44.252 --> 00:07:48.172
predisposition gene. If you focus in on just early

136
00:07:48.272 --> 00:07:52.122
onset cancers that would be most amenable to newborn screening, it's

137
00:07:52.172 --> 00:07:56.072
about 5%, with TP53 and RB1

138
00:07:56.172 --> 00:08:00.152
being the most common, APC and DICER being also very

139
00:08:00.272 --> 00:08:04.152
frequently found. Lots of other genes have one to three individuals.

140
00:08:05.532 --> 00:08:08.212
Some people say, "Well, why don't you use family history?" Well, many

141
00:08:09.612 --> 00:08:13.212
of these patients have de novo mutations. That's very common.

142
00:08:13.452 --> 00:08:16.992
80% of patients with RB1. So family history is

143
00:08:17.032 --> 00:08:20.502
irrelevant. And more importantly, in the United States,

144
00:08:20.872 --> 00:08:24.632
many of these patients are diagnosed with advanced tumors or actually from

145
00:08:24.712 --> 00:08:28.652
families with known genetic diagnoses, and that information

146
00:08:28.712 --> 00:08:30.782
was never conveyed to the pediatrician.

147
00:08:32.052 --> 00:08:36.033
And that can be because of low penetrance, or really it's often just they never

148
00:08:36.072 --> 00:08:37.393
think to tell the doctor.

149
00:08:38.893 --> 00:08:42.543
So the question, of course, then becomes, if you're going to do

150
00:08:42.672 --> 00:08:46.552
newborn screening, do we know what to do with the positive children?

151
00:08:47.052 --> 00:08:49.412
And here I do want to acknowledge AACR.

152
00:08:49.732 --> 00:08:49.892
I

153
00:08:52.252 --> 00:08:56.012
know David's here, and maybe Garrett's here, co-chaired a committee of which I was

154
00:08:56.052 --> 00:08:59.752
a member that did two childhood cancer

155
00:08:59.772 --> 00:09:03.572
predisposition workshops, and that included more

156
00:09:03.622 --> 00:09:07.352
than 65 oncologists and other specialists, geneticists,

157
00:09:07.432 --> 00:09:08.252
radiologists,

158
00:09:09.112 --> 00:09:12.372
from 11 countries. And the goal was to develop

159
00:09:12.432 --> 00:09:16.012
evidence-based guidelines for children diagnosed with cancer

160
00:09:16.112 --> 00:09:19.752
predisposition syndromes. We worked closely with AACR and the

161
00:09:19.792 --> 00:09:22.352
Clinical Cancer Research Journal to publish these.

162
00:09:23.172 --> 00:09:26.632
And I'm proud to say that we did develop guidelines for over 50

163
00:09:26.712 --> 00:09:30.512
syndromes. They were first published in 2017, and we

164
00:09:30.532 --> 00:09:34.172
did 20 updates in '24, '25. They're all open

165
00:09:34.212 --> 00:09:37.632
access. Please feel free to photograph the slide.

166
00:09:38.132 --> 00:09:41.752
And these provide standard guidelines starting at infancy for

167
00:09:41.872 --> 00:09:43.741
cancer predisposition in children.

168
00:09:44.972 --> 00:09:48.732
Okay, so now we know the conditions. We have some idea of the rate.

169
00:09:49.432 --> 00:09:53.012
Can we do this? So Lisa Diller and her colleague Jennifer Yeh

170
00:09:53.252 --> 00:09:57.132
published a few years ago a modeling of this using a

171
00:09:57.992 --> 00:10:01.932
next generation sequencing panel for the set of genes in the

172
00:10:01.972 --> 00:10:05.852
middle. They used public databases to estimate their

173
00:10:05.892 --> 00:10:09.152
findings, and then they estimated outcomes and

174
00:10:09.192 --> 00:10:13.172
costs. And overall, they showed that if you did do

175
00:10:13.232 --> 00:10:17.142
new cancer risk newborn screening, cancer deaths before the age of

176
00:10:17.392 --> 00:10:20.952
20 would decrease by 8%. For those with a cancer

177
00:10:21.012 --> 00:10:23.872
predisposition syndrome, it might decrease by as much as

178
00:10:23.912 --> 00:10:27.332
54%, and more adult survivors would be

179
00:10:27.392 --> 00:10:31.172
alive because radiation was avoided, and you knew which

180
00:10:31.232 --> 00:10:35.192
individuals were more likely to develop a second malignancy, and

181
00:10:35.232 --> 00:10:39.152
you also saw an improvement in outcome due to the shift to

182
00:10:39.212 --> 00:10:40.292
earlier stages.

183
00:10:41.992 --> 00:10:45.972
And they found that the cost effectiveness of the testing was almost

184
00:10:45.992 --> 00:10:49.892
completely driven by the sequencing costs, which influenced the

185
00:10:50.592 --> 00:10:52.192
study that we've now put together.

186
00:10:53.682 --> 00:10:57.432
They've also done a retrospective study working with Michigan on their

187
00:10:57.552 --> 00:11:01.292
cancer registry and their newborn blood spot bank,

188
00:11:01.852 --> 00:11:05.392
and they were able to link the blood spots of children who

189
00:11:05.652 --> 00:11:09.052
then developed a tumor by the age of eight, and they

190
00:11:09.072 --> 00:11:12.652
identified almost 2,000 individuals where they were able to

191
00:11:12.692 --> 00:11:16.502
obtain the blood spots. And the laboratory at the Brigham and Women,

192
00:11:16.612 --> 00:11:20.542
and this is data that's currently under review, then did next generation

193
00:11:20.692 --> 00:11:24.512
sequencing of a 3.2 millimeter dried blood spot,

194
00:11:24.572 --> 00:11:27.552
getting adequate DNA to get the results.

195
00:11:27.752 --> 00:11:31.552
They used AI supported variant classification

196
00:11:31.632 --> 00:11:35.452
as well as manual interpretation to call the variant, and then, of

197
00:11:35.552 --> 00:11:39.492
course, analyze the data. So this is just a small snapshot of their

198
00:11:39.552 --> 00:11:42.612
data. First of all, there were concordance of results.

199
00:11:43.232 --> 00:11:47.012
The five children of the 2,000 who had a RET variant all

200
00:11:47.072 --> 00:11:50.492
had medullary thyroid cancer. The much larger number of

201
00:11:50.552 --> 00:11:53.752
children who had an RB1 variant, all had

202
00:11:53.892 --> 00:11:57.372
retinoblastoma or pinealblastoma.

203
00:11:57.812 --> 00:12:01.692
So the genes did in fact match the tumors these children went on to

204
00:12:01.712 --> 00:12:02.172
develop.

205
00:12:03.332 --> 00:12:07.072
Overall, they saw rates that are very similar to what I had reported.

206
00:12:07.592 --> 00:12:11.432
Of the whole cohort of 2,000, about 6.8%

207
00:12:11.512 --> 00:12:15.472
had a pathogenic or likely pathogenic variant in this small

208
00:12:15.572 --> 00:12:19.252
group of genes. And again, these genes were selected because they're associated

209
00:12:19.292 --> 00:12:23.252
with early onset cancer. Genes like BRCA1 and things

210
00:12:23.272 --> 00:12:27.248
like that were not included.They estimate about one

211
00:12:27.308 --> 00:12:29.168
in 30,000 children who

212
00:12:29.388 --> 00:12:33.348
have a positive blood spot might go

213
00:12:33.408 --> 00:12:36.828
on to develop cancer. And that's very

214
00:12:37.008 --> 00:12:40.528
similar to other newborn screening, which includes very, very rare

215
00:12:40.628 --> 00:12:41.308
conditions.

216
00:12:42.268 --> 00:12:46.138
What they don't know is how many positives might not have developed a

217
00:12:46.168 --> 00:12:48.908
tumor, and that's one of the things we're going to look at in our study.

218
00:12:50.108 --> 00:12:53.868
So with all of that, Lisa and I and many of our colleagues in Houston and Boston

219
00:12:53.928 --> 00:12:57.408
got together and proposed to the Alex's Lemonade Stand Foundation

220
00:12:57.888 --> 00:12:57.968
a

221
00:12:59.548 --> 00:13:02.468
study that we now call NCARE with this

222
00:13:02.528 --> 00:13:06.208
multi-institutional team. I do want to point out that we also

223
00:13:06.248 --> 00:13:09.448
included Natasha Bonhomme from Expecting Health.

224
00:13:09.878 --> 00:13:13.508
That organization works to

225
00:13:13.568 --> 00:13:15.668
educate parents on newborn screening.

226
00:13:16.508 --> 00:13:20.388
And we included neonatologists, OBGYNs, geneticists, and

227
00:13:20.428 --> 00:13:23.488
oncologists in our team, as well as epidemiologists.

228
00:13:24.928 --> 00:13:28.628
So what are we proposing to do? And we've just finished our first

229
00:13:28.728 --> 00:13:32.128
year. We're using pooling method for a

230
00:13:32.188 --> 00:13:35.988
population-based cost sensitive testing, thinking again about the

231
00:13:36.108 --> 00:13:39.978
modeling that the cost of the test is a major driver, and I'll

232
00:13:40.008 --> 00:13:42.928
talk about that more in a minute. We then have

233
00:13:42.988 --> 00:13:46.848
identified a very large set of controls from Michigan who

234
00:13:46.928 --> 00:13:50.668
did not develop cancer, so we can now compare what proportion of the

235
00:13:50.728 --> 00:13:52.808
controls might have a positive test.

236
00:13:53.548 --> 00:13:57.088
And we're developing educational materials for parents on

237
00:13:57.208 --> 00:14:01.108
cancer risk newborn screening. We're then proposing to launch

238
00:14:01.188 --> 00:14:04.508
a large prospective clinical trial in Houston and

239
00:14:04.568 --> 00:14:08.348
Boston to assess feasibility of doing this testing at scale.

240
00:14:08.908 --> 00:14:11.928
Our goal is to approach 10,000 mothers of newborns,

241
00:14:12.508 --> 00:14:16.388
measure acceptability for parents for a focused versus broad

242
00:14:16.448 --> 00:14:17.568
testing. And the

243
00:14:18.448 --> 00:14:22.318
focus is like RB1 and WT1, high de novo

244
00:14:22.508 --> 00:14:25.308
rate, high penetrance, early onset.

245
00:14:25.768 --> 00:14:29.488
Genes like DICER1, for example, have very early-- A mother I just

246
00:14:29.588 --> 00:14:32.648
saw on Wednesday said, "Well, not everyone with DICER1 gets cancer."

247
00:14:33.588 --> 00:14:37.428
And her child had a PPB. But in fact, if you

248
00:14:37.488 --> 00:14:41.268
look at the data, the penetrance is only about 10% for any

249
00:14:41.308 --> 00:14:45.218
malignancy. So the larger panel does include genes where

250
00:14:45.248 --> 00:14:49.028
the penetrance is not as high, but there's still risk in early

251
00:14:49.148 --> 00:14:52.408
onset disease, like pulmonary

252
00:14:52.428 --> 00:14:56.248
pleuroblastoma. And of course, we want to identify the potential

253
00:14:56.348 --> 00:14:59.808
harms and risks and the family health impact.

254
00:15:00.968 --> 00:15:04.728
So Andy Bhattacharjee from the Brigham and Women's Hospital

255
00:15:04.848 --> 00:15:07.248
is running the molecular lab for this study.

256
00:15:07.428 --> 00:15:11.128
We're using a pooling test that was published a few years ago in

257
00:15:11.168 --> 00:15:14.968
Genome Medicine, where every sample is in two

258
00:15:15.028 --> 00:15:19.008
pools of 10 samples, and therefore, by looking at

259
00:15:19.048 --> 00:15:22.948
the overall results of these 20 pools

260
00:15:23.008 --> 00:15:26.708
from the 100 samples, you can identify the specific

261
00:15:27.248 --> 00:15:29.338
sample that had to have the mutation.

262
00:15:29.788 --> 00:15:33.248
And this saves you de-convoluting every positive pool.

263
00:15:33.958 --> 00:15:37.688
We're using element sequencing instruments, which are being adapted by

264
00:15:37.697 --> 00:15:40.548
many newborn screening providers.

265
00:15:40.588 --> 00:15:44.408
We are again, using AI driven informatics to aid in variant

266
00:15:44.428 --> 00:15:48.408
classification. And the pipeline is designed to yield cost

267
00:15:48.448 --> 00:15:51.848
of testing within the newborn screening test range.

268
00:15:53.048 --> 00:15:56.968
This is the trial which we hope to get underway in a year, where again,

269
00:15:56.988 --> 00:16:00.948
we're going to randomize mothers to either the focus panel or the full panel,

270
00:16:01.468 --> 00:16:04.588
look at their acceptability of these two options.

271
00:16:04.608 --> 00:16:07.408
We're obviously going to probe reasons for declining.

272
00:16:08.328 --> 00:16:09.928
Everyone will get a baseline

273
00:16:11.508 --> 00:16:15.348
demographic survey, but a subset will get a much more detailed

274
00:16:15.408 --> 00:16:18.928
survey about cancer risk, cancer worry, and then we will

275
00:16:18.968 --> 00:16:21.448
repeat that six months after the test.

276
00:16:22.008 --> 00:16:25.958
We expect very few positives out of 10,000 babies, but if

277
00:16:25.988 --> 00:16:29.648
we do find any, those parents will be interviewed as well as their

278
00:16:29.708 --> 00:16:30.428
pediatrician.

279
00:16:31.788 --> 00:16:35.528
Of course, I'm talking about targeted sequencing, but there's a lot going on

280
00:16:35.708 --> 00:16:39.148
in whole genome sequencing, and this is a graphic from the UK

281
00:16:39.248 --> 00:16:43.168
Generation study about the many steps in doing whole genome

282
00:16:43.267 --> 00:16:43.848
sequencing.

283
00:16:45.068 --> 00:16:49.048
And there are now many genome sequencing studies, but again, they are

284
00:16:49.068 --> 00:16:52.548
reporting very few cancer predisposition genes.

285
00:16:52.648 --> 00:16:56.228
So iCONS is now this international organization of sub

286
00:16:56.328 --> 00:16:59.408
studies, which NCARE is now a member of.

287
00:16:59.488 --> 00:17:03.108
A medical student at Harvard reviewed 22 trials with

288
00:17:03.128 --> 00:17:06.709
available gene lists, and only RB1 was in the

289
00:17:06.729 --> 00:17:07.429
majority.

290
00:17:08.469 --> 00:17:11.508
RET and WT1 were in about half of the studies.

291
00:17:12.308 --> 00:17:16.008
Tuber sclerosis, frankly, was probably there because of the epilepsy risk,

292
00:17:16.128 --> 00:17:20.108
not the cancer risk. So you can see that even in these whole genome studies,

293
00:17:20.229 --> 00:17:24.068
some of which are reporting 400 genes, only one or two

294
00:17:24.148 --> 00:17:26.087
cancer genes are being included.

295
00:17:27.709 --> 00:17:29.508
This is an example from Generation.

296
00:17:29.568 --> 00:17:33.288
They did identify a child with RB1, going back to my first

297
00:17:33.708 --> 00:17:37.288
case. This child was unidentified before this.

298
00:17:37.458 --> 00:17:41.248
Did have small bilateral tumors that were amenable to

299
00:17:41.948 --> 00:17:43.808
simpler, less toxic treatment.

300
00:17:45.108 --> 00:17:48.768
And this has now made the press in the UK and made them

301
00:17:48.828 --> 00:17:52.368
reconsider perhaps adding some additional cancer genes.

302
00:17:53.208 --> 00:17:56.888
In the US, there's a study that was just funded last

303
00:17:56.968 --> 00:18:00.748
summer called BEacons. It's a large NIH funded collaborative

304
00:18:00.848 --> 00:18:04.568
research team. There's seven state labs participating.

305
00:18:05.168 --> 00:18:08.948
They plan to sequence up to 30,000 babies, and the

306
00:18:09.028 --> 00:18:11.968
whole genome sequencing is being done by GeneDx.

307
00:18:12.508 --> 00:18:16.148
And they developed a list of 777 conditions,

308
00:18:16.688 --> 00:18:19.548
which were just announced. I'm happy to say that

309
00:18:21.008 --> 00:18:23.828
Lisa and I both got to participate on the committee.

310
00:18:24.148 --> 00:18:27.428
And there are 19 cancer genes included on this

311
00:18:27.488 --> 00:18:29.836
list.So to finish,

312
00:18:30.716 --> 00:18:34.376
expanded newborn screening clinical trials are beginning to include

313
00:18:34.416 --> 00:18:38.336
genetic risk for pediatric cancer, which represents a potential major

314
00:18:38.396 --> 00:18:40.006
advance in preventive medicine.

315
00:18:40.876 --> 00:18:44.656
Improved sequencing modalities and pooling strategies may enable

316
00:18:44.816 --> 00:18:48.556
cost-effective identification. Remember, the states have to pay for this.

317
00:18:48.596 --> 00:18:51.936
Texas alone has 400,000 babies a year,

318
00:18:52.556 --> 00:18:56.296
so whole genome sequencing is probably not realistic

319
00:18:56.396 --> 00:19:00.316
without NIH support. We hope that it will improve

320
00:19:00.376 --> 00:19:04.236
outcomes with early detection through newborn screening and improve

321
00:19:04.356 --> 00:19:08.296
surveillance using the guidelines AACR helped to develop to

322
00:19:08.316 --> 00:19:11.376
result in better survival with less toxic treatments.

323
00:19:11.996 --> 00:19:15.836
And of course, these children require evidence-based

324
00:19:15.876 --> 00:19:19.736
protocols, attention to incomplete penetrance, and family

325
00:19:19.776 --> 00:19:23.196
support systems. But given the rest of the talks,

326
00:19:23.656 --> 00:19:27.136
this provides exciting new opportunities for cancer prevention

327
00:19:27.216 --> 00:19:29.156
research in children. Thank you.

328
00:19:33.916 --> 00:19:37.716
Thanks, Sharon. Next speaker will be John Burn from Newcastle

329
00:19:37.796 --> 00:19:41.256
University. John's going to talk about therapeutic

330
00:19:41.376 --> 00:19:45.076
precision cancer prevention, the power of canaries.

331
00:19:48.076 --> 00:19:48.356
So...

332
00:19:48.876 --> 00:19:51.616
Thank you, Mr. Chair. Ladies and gentlemen, my name is John Burn.

333
00:19:51.756 --> 00:19:55.576
I'm from the UK. It practically stands for the ungrateful kingdom now.

334
00:19:56.976 --> 00:19:59.416
So I'm going to talk about canaries.

335
00:20:00.016 --> 00:20:01.116
These are my disclosures.

336
00:20:02.176 --> 00:20:05.956
Thirty six years ago, I went to a local coal mine and

337
00:20:06.016 --> 00:20:07.796
asked for a picture of one of their canaries.

338
00:20:08.416 --> 00:20:11.796
I'd just been to see a 12-year-old boy called Jonathan, whose mother had a

339
00:20:11.816 --> 00:20:14.516
panproctocolectomy for familial polyposis.

340
00:20:15.096 --> 00:20:18.996
He had a clear colonoscopy, but he had osteomas just like his mother, which meant

341
00:20:19.036 --> 00:20:22.836
that he was a gene carrier. And it struck me that here was a perfect opportunity to

342
00:20:22.896 --> 00:20:26.736
try prevention strategies, not only to prevent problems

343
00:20:26.816 --> 00:20:30.736
in people with FAP, but also as a model for the general population.

344
00:20:31.576 --> 00:20:35.276
And I persuaded my colleagues, Tim Bishop in Leeds, and John Mather, our

345
00:20:35.336 --> 00:20:39.016
professor of human nutrition, and we identified two potential interventions,

346
00:20:39.216 --> 00:20:42.396
fermentable fiber or resistant starch, and aspirin.

347
00:20:43.126 --> 00:20:46.716
And we set up CAP1, which was eventually published under Ray's

348
00:20:47.376 --> 00:20:48.816
editorship in the,

349
00:20:49.796 --> 00:20:52.286
Cancer Prevention Research quite a long time after.

350
00:20:52.316 --> 00:20:53.776
It was quite a hard trial to do, but it

351
00:20:54.656 --> 00:20:58.376
ironically started recruiting in 1993, just as we were supporting

352
00:20:59.376 --> 00:21:03.076
Kolodner's group to identify the MSH2 gene for Lynch syndrome.

353
00:21:03.526 --> 00:21:05.976
And that was an altogether better target population.

354
00:21:06.576 --> 00:21:10.236
So I persuaded the leaders in that field to come to Newcastle, including Henry

355
00:21:10.256 --> 00:21:14.156
Lynch, and we decided to do CAP2, which would be the same approach

356
00:21:14.516 --> 00:21:18.445
using the same interventions, slightly modified in terms of using enteric-coated

357
00:21:18.496 --> 00:21:22.436
aspirin and a commercially available resistant starch.

358
00:21:22.996 --> 00:21:26.556
And we started that in 1999, and when we eventually

359
00:21:26.596 --> 00:21:30.076
completed recruitment in 2005, we followed through to

360
00:21:30.256 --> 00:21:33.036
2011, when we could see the aspirin was working.

361
00:21:33.385 --> 00:21:37.256
So we then decided to plan a new trial, imaginatively called

362
00:21:37.296 --> 00:21:40.376
CAP3, to do a dose non-inferiority study.

363
00:21:41.136 --> 00:21:43.176
Meanwhile, we finished the CAP2 trial.

364
00:21:43.216 --> 00:21:47.136
We went out to the 10-year unblinding stage, and we

365
00:21:47.176 --> 00:21:50.876
were able, with our national registry, to continue following the English,

366
00:21:51.096 --> 00:21:54.676
Welsh, and Finnish patients through to the next decade.

367
00:21:54.706 --> 00:21:58.516
And you can see that despite the fact we stopped giving them any aspirin after four

368
00:21:58.536 --> 00:22:02.445
years, the benefits were persisting for several years thereafter,

369
00:22:02.556 --> 00:22:05.596
presumably destroying premalignant lesions as a result.

370
00:22:06.896 --> 00:22:10.776
The other thing to remember is that nothing happens for the first four

371
00:22:10.816 --> 00:22:14.136
years. When you do prevention, you don't instantly see an effect.

372
00:22:14.616 --> 00:22:18.536
And that's very important in terms of interpretation because hazard

373
00:22:18.596 --> 00:22:22.356
ratio looks at the first event and therefore is not the

374
00:22:22.516 --> 00:22:26.356
ideal statistical approach. And so we also used incidence

375
00:22:26.436 --> 00:22:30.256
ratio, negative binomial regression, which allows you to account for

376
00:22:30.356 --> 00:22:32.436
all of the cancers rather than just the first one.

377
00:22:33.716 --> 00:22:37.336
The second limb of the trial took a long time to get published, and I'm grateful to

378
00:22:37.356 --> 00:22:41.256
Ray for helping us to find referees who didn't have a religious objection

379
00:22:41.296 --> 00:22:43.556
to randomized control trials involving food.

380
00:22:44.376 --> 00:22:48.316
And we eventually got this published because the primary impact was not as

381
00:22:48.355 --> 00:22:52.116
we expected. It didn't affect the development of colorectal cancer in Lynch

382
00:22:52.156 --> 00:22:55.736
syndrome, but it did rather dramatically impact on our secondary

383
00:22:55.776 --> 00:22:59.096
endpoint, which were the other Lynch syndrome cancers, which were about

384
00:22:59.276 --> 00:23:03.216
50% down. And the biggest impact seemed to be on the upper GI

385
00:23:03.336 --> 00:23:05.216
cancers, hepatobiliary, duodenal.

386
00:23:05.906 --> 00:23:09.536
And we suspected that that might be because we changed the microbiome in

387
00:23:09.596 --> 00:23:12.916
these individuals, and

388
00:23:13.736 --> 00:23:17.416
that resulted in a reduction in the production of carcinogenic secondary

389
00:23:17.656 --> 00:23:21.356
bile acids, which of course recycle through the upper GI

390
00:23:21.456 --> 00:23:25.276
tract. Whatever explanation, having a high fiber diet is great,

391
00:23:25.576 --> 00:23:28.116
but you don't have to eat green bananas. We did get a cover.

392
00:23:28.496 --> 00:23:32.116
I've had more questions about green bananas in the last few years than I ever want

393
00:23:32.156 --> 00:23:33.016
to recount.

394
00:23:33.476 --> 00:23:34.296
Sorry about that.

395
00:23:35.756 --> 00:23:35.996
So

396
00:23:37.256 --> 00:23:41.216
CAP3 was primarily supported by our National Institute of Health

397
00:23:41.296 --> 00:23:44.256
Research, and we recruited across all the genetic centers in the UK,

398
00:23:44.536 --> 00:23:47.746
1,547 people as we were targeting.

399
00:23:47.776 --> 00:23:51.406
We also managed to supplement that with setting the trial up separately in,

400
00:23:51.706 --> 00:23:54.476
as you can see, Australia, Finland, Spain, and Israel.

401
00:23:54.596 --> 00:23:58.236
And all of that data came into the Newcastle database for analysis.

402
00:23:59.156 --> 00:24:03.016
We had lots of discussions about how to design the statistics, and we wanted to

403
00:24:03.096 --> 00:24:06.996
do two separate analyses comparing the 600 milligram dose

404
00:24:07.076 --> 00:24:10.856
with a 300 milligram dose, which we thought would probably work, and

405
00:24:10.936 --> 00:24:13.956
comparing 600 to 100, which we thought might not.

406
00:24:14.556 --> 00:24:17.936
And so we overloaded the 600 milligram group after much

407
00:24:17.976 --> 00:24:21.356
consultation, and randomized on a four to three

408
00:24:21.776 --> 00:24:25.736
basis. We blinded for two years so we could look at the

409
00:24:25.796 --> 00:24:29.416
adverse events, but we kept on going for a further three years so that we could get

410
00:24:29.436 --> 00:24:31.676
the maximum impact across a five-year

411
00:24:31.816 --> 00:24:35.740
follow-up.The randomization went exactly as

412
00:24:35.800 --> 00:24:39.720
we hoped, and as you can see, mostly recruited MSH2 and

413
00:24:39.820 --> 00:24:43.740
MLH1 gene carriers. These are the high penetrance group who tend to be

414
00:24:43.800 --> 00:24:45.240
more seen in our hospitals.

415
00:24:47.280 --> 00:24:48.420
So apologies for the slightly

416
00:24:49.580 --> 00:24:52.900
out-of-focus picture here. This is from our supplementary document which is just

417
00:24:52.980 --> 00:24:56.320
about to appear in "Lancet Gastroenterology." It hasn't quite got out this week.

418
00:24:56.960 --> 00:25:00.720
And the rather surprising result was that we had the fewest Lynch

419
00:25:00.780 --> 00:25:04.140
syndrome cancers in the people on the smallest dose of aspirin.

420
00:25:04.760 --> 00:25:08.240
The 300 milligram group did rather worse, but as you can see, that was mostly

421
00:25:08.300 --> 00:25:12.140
because they went high in the first three or four years when, remember, the

422
00:25:12.220 --> 00:25:16.020
aspirin is not really having much of an effect, and then kind of tracked back into

423
00:25:16.060 --> 00:25:18.920
the confidence intervals of the 600 milligram group thereafter.

424
00:25:20.460 --> 00:25:23.820
This slide includes bladder and prostate cancers, which are now seen as Lynch

425
00:25:23.860 --> 00:25:24.340
syndrome.

426
00:25:26.320 --> 00:25:29.340
The other thing we looked at was a secondary endpoint of colorectal cancers, and

427
00:25:29.400 --> 00:25:32.960
again, the 100 milligram group had the fewest colorectal cancers, which was

428
00:25:33.020 --> 00:25:35.390
obviously slightly surprising, but great news.

429
00:25:37.840 --> 00:25:40.500
Now, this is a slightly complicated slide, but we thought the best way of

430
00:25:40.580 --> 00:25:43.720
representing this data collectively was as a forest plot.

431
00:25:44.460 --> 00:25:47.420
We chose an upper limit, a predetermined upper limit of

432
00:25:47.640 --> 00:25:51.380
1.5. The reason for that was that we saw a 50%

433
00:25:51.420 --> 00:25:55.410
reduction in colon cancer in CAPP2 with 600 milligrams,

434
00:25:55.500 --> 00:25:59.360
but we did a survey of general practitioners of over 1,000 and found that

435
00:25:59.420 --> 00:26:03.320
only 62% of them would be willing to prescribe 600 milligrams of aspirin

436
00:26:03.360 --> 00:26:06.880
even if we told them to. And so if we got a

437
00:26:07.120 --> 00:26:11.100
25% reduction with a baby aspirin, we figured that would be worth having.

438
00:26:11.340 --> 00:26:13.740
And so that was where we set the predetermined limit.

439
00:26:13.760 --> 00:26:17.620
And you can see that the confidence intervals of all of the interventions for Lynch

440
00:26:17.680 --> 00:26:21.160
syndrome cancer, for colorectal cancer, and for all cancers were

441
00:26:21.240 --> 00:26:25.140
inside that 1.5 threshold. That was great until

442
00:26:25.200 --> 00:26:27.300
we got to the referee for "The Lancet."

443
00:26:28.280 --> 00:26:30.580
And it turns out statisticians argue a lot.

444
00:26:31.260 --> 00:26:33.920
And the statistician who was reviewing it said, "No, no, no.

445
00:26:34.060 --> 00:26:37.860
Even though you had a big reference group, it's still multiple testing, so you

446
00:26:37.920 --> 00:26:41.780
have to use 97.5% confidence intervals." So we

447
00:26:41.840 --> 00:26:42.060
did,

448
00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:46.620
and we eventually put both in the paper, which has now got rather long.

449
00:26:47.080 --> 00:26:50.920
The good news is it was still inside the threshold, and in fact,

450
00:26:51.020 --> 00:26:54.840
if you are addicted to HR, it was inside the threshold there as

451
00:26:54.880 --> 00:26:58.180
well, but that's as close as you can get to the threshold without actually going

452
00:26:58.240 --> 00:26:58.600
over it.

453
00:27:00.240 --> 00:27:03.740
The downside of having to go to 97.5% was we slipped

454
00:27:03.820 --> 00:27:06.160
slightly over the line on the per protocol group.

455
00:27:06.380 --> 00:27:10.210
Now, if you're a purist in non-inferiority trials, which I wasn't,

456
00:27:12.100 --> 00:27:15.690
it turns out that you have to get across the line on per protocol as well,

457
00:27:15.760 --> 00:27:19.489
because obviously if you think about it, if everyone just didn't take the tablets,

458
00:27:19.560 --> 00:27:23.380
then everything would be the same, and so you need to know they took the tablets.

459
00:27:23.420 --> 00:27:27.080
But of course, we had the CAPP2 trial, and the CAPP2 trial showed us that the

460
00:27:27.300 --> 00:27:30.840
600 milligram group in CAPP3 did exactly the same as the ones in

461
00:27:30.880 --> 00:27:33.520
CAPP2, so we can be pretty sure they took their tablets.

462
00:27:33.580 --> 00:27:37.220
So the intention to treat data is the reliable result.

463
00:27:38.670 --> 00:27:42.049
The other thing we just did as an afterthought was just said, what if we just put

464
00:27:42.160 --> 00:27:45.880
all of the CAPP3 patients together and looked at their risk

465
00:27:46.040 --> 00:27:49.860
compared to the old CAPP2 graph? And you can see that the

466
00:27:49.900 --> 00:27:53.560
pink confidence intervals here are actually tighter than the CAPP2 data because

467
00:27:53.600 --> 00:27:56.950
it's a bigger series. And in fact, we got an HR of

468
00:27:57.020 --> 00:28:00.960
0.67 comparing all of our CAPP3 patients

469
00:28:01.020 --> 00:28:04.200
to that historic placebo group in CAPP2.

470
00:28:04.900 --> 00:28:08.360
We're going to go on now and assemble a new reference group from our

471
00:28:08.440 --> 00:28:10.100
database I'll tell you about in a moment.

472
00:28:11.080 --> 00:28:14.720
On serious adverse events, the good news was there were none in the 100 milligram

473
00:28:14.800 --> 00:28:17.420
group. Not all of these were due to aspirin.

474
00:28:17.500 --> 00:28:20.180
One of them was someone who fell off his mountain bike, and another one was a

475
00:28:20.340 --> 00:28:23.420
surgeon who cut an artery, but you have to report them all.

476
00:28:24.100 --> 00:28:27.960
But the good news is that we didn't see any major hospital treatment events

477
00:28:28.480 --> 00:28:29.060
of people

478
00:28:29.900 --> 00:28:33.680
in the 100 milligram group. In terms of events of interest, these were

479
00:28:33.720 --> 00:28:37.230
relatively small in number considering we're looking at several, about 8,000

480
00:28:37.320 --> 00:28:41.000
patient years of follow-up, and the majority of these were just complaints about

481
00:28:41.080 --> 00:28:41.580
bruising,

482
00:28:42.620 --> 00:28:45.980
which of course is an inevitable consequence of an antiplatelet dose of aspirin,

483
00:28:46.320 --> 00:28:49.880
something that I think your president has had to draw attention to in the not too

484
00:28:49.940 --> 00:28:53.220
distant future. And speaking of your president, he'll be pleased to know that there

485
00:28:53.240 --> 00:28:56.079
were no cases of autism in our trial.

486
00:28:59.020 --> 00:29:02.909
So in summary, after eight years of treatment, 30% of people

487
00:29:02.960 --> 00:29:06.540
on the smallest dose had the fewest cancers, so we should be recommending low-dose

488
00:29:06.600 --> 00:29:08.200
aspirin to people with Lynch syndrome.

489
00:29:08.650 --> 00:29:11.960
And in the UK, we've already, since most of the people who write the guidelines are

490
00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:15.320
authors on the paper, have already changed our guideline, which will be coming out

491
00:29:15.880 --> 00:29:17.940
online very soon, as soon as the paper arrives.

492
00:29:18.220 --> 00:29:21.979
And we're basically saying give everyone, in your case, 81 milligrams of

493
00:29:22.060 --> 00:29:25.940
aspirin. And we're suggesting that we start at five years prior to

494
00:29:25.960 --> 00:29:29.940
colonoscopy and stop at 70 because, of course, the side effects are much

495
00:29:30.020 --> 00:29:33.460
higher and possibly less efficacious in the older population.

496
00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:36.960
Eradicate H. pylori, deal with blood pressure to cut side effects.

497
00:29:37.540 --> 00:29:41.060
And an interesting, important bit of information we need to build on is

498
00:29:41.120 --> 00:29:45.060
obesity. We think you should double the dose for people with a BMI of

499
00:29:45.180 --> 00:29:45.880
over 30.

500
00:29:47.320 --> 00:29:50.940
Why does it work? Well, I haven't got time in my 15 minutes of fame to discuss all

501
00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:54.930
of these options. It's clearly not COX-2 inhibition because although that did get

502
00:29:54.960 --> 00:29:57.590
me my most cited publication, thanks to Monica,

503
00:29:58.500 --> 00:30:02.400
it isn't usable in our population because of the adverse event

504
00:30:02.460 --> 00:30:06.360
risk. And of course, a small dose of aspirin is not going to block COX-2.

505
00:30:07.320 --> 00:30:11.160
Much interest now in the mTOR pathway after Andy Chan's group first pointed

506
00:30:11.240 --> 00:30:14.820
out that it seems to be the PIK3CA mutated tumors that respond,

507
00:30:15.400 --> 00:30:19.340
and this very nice review explains all of the places where in that

508
00:30:19.400 --> 00:30:23.120
pathway aspirin can have an effect because aspirin is a natural substance.

509
00:30:23.180 --> 00:30:26.800
Our natural diet used to contain a lot of salicylate because

510
00:30:26.840 --> 00:30:30.620
plants produce salicylate to cause apoptosis.

511
00:30:30.640 --> 00:30:32.910
So another question is, is the aspirin enhancing

512
00:30:32.980 --> 00:30:36.640
apoptosis?If that is the case, it would explain perhaps in

513
00:30:36.780 --> 00:30:40.660
part why it works less well in people of my age, because about 10% of

514
00:30:40.700 --> 00:30:44.460
my crypts have no longer got functioning mitochondria, and so

515
00:30:44.480 --> 00:30:47.960
apoptosis fades with age. But the most

516
00:30:48.040 --> 00:30:51.860
interesting, exciting result is what you're going to hear about more from my

517
00:30:51.940 --> 00:30:55.900
partner, Ruth Langley, tomorrow in her presentation, and our partners

518
00:30:55.980 --> 00:30:59.860
at Cambridge, who've demonstrated that in fact it's the activated platelets we need

519
00:30:59.900 --> 00:31:00.680
to watch out for.

520
00:31:01.640 --> 00:31:03.200
So Ruth will be talking about this.

521
00:31:03.240 --> 00:31:07.160
It's Rahul's group in Cambridge, published

522
00:31:07.200 --> 00:31:11.110
in "Nature" last year, that activated platelets are really not

523
00:31:11.160 --> 00:31:14.680
nice, and they produce all manner of bad prostaglandins, including thromboxane

524
00:31:14.740 --> 00:31:18.240
A2, which we've known for a long time is a predictor of bad

525
00:31:18.340 --> 00:31:22.260
outcomes in health. It turns out TXA2 hits your T

526
00:31:22.360 --> 00:31:25.800
cells, and through the guanine receptor pathway, it

527
00:31:25.920 --> 00:31:29.140
inhibits tumor response. And Rahul's team took out

528
00:31:29.260 --> 00:31:32.620
RGF1 and negated that effect to demonstrate the point.

529
00:31:33.360 --> 00:31:37.200
If you take aspirin, you permanently inactivate COX1, you take out

530
00:31:37.260 --> 00:31:41.040
your activated platelets, and that enhances your

531
00:31:41.100 --> 00:31:44.620
tumor response as a result. That was about two years of

532
00:31:44.660 --> 00:31:47.240
reviewing and five years of research in one slide.

533
00:31:48.620 --> 00:31:52.460
So where are all the canaries? One in 400 of the people in our UK Biobank are

534
00:31:52.500 --> 00:31:56.060
supposed to be suffering from Lynch

535
00:31:56.080 --> 00:31:59.400
syndrome, and yet when we set up

536
00:31:59.440 --> 00:32:03.420
CAPP2, sorry, CAPP3, we could find about 8,000 people

537
00:32:03.440 --> 00:32:04.920
in our country with Lynch syndrome.

538
00:32:06.380 --> 00:32:10.180
So we persuaded NICE to make it a requirement that all

539
00:32:10.240 --> 00:32:14.110
people with colon cancer be tested for mismatch repair deficiency in their

540
00:32:14.200 --> 00:32:17.620
tumor to help target people who might have Lynch syndrome.

541
00:32:18.540 --> 00:32:22.080
And with my colleagues at the National Disease Registration Service,

542
00:32:22.200 --> 00:32:26.100
we rather tiringly looked at all 37,662

543
00:32:26.200 --> 00:32:30.020
colorectal cancers that happened in England in 2019, and we

544
00:32:30.060 --> 00:32:33.500
found that only 43% of them had actually been tested by either

545
00:32:33.620 --> 00:32:37.460
MSI or immunohistochemistry. And rather worryingly, only

546
00:32:38.060 --> 00:32:41.500
210 of those people who were positive actually made it to a

547
00:32:41.560 --> 00:32:42.520
germline test.

548
00:32:43.339 --> 00:32:46.990
So that led our NHS England team to agree to fund a transformation

549
00:32:47.080 --> 00:32:50.960
project, which is chaired by Kevin Monahan, and we've now got to more than

550
00:32:51.220 --> 00:32:54.960
95% of our tumors being tested either by

551
00:32:55.060 --> 00:32:59.020
IHC or by MSI testing. And I'm excited to

552
00:32:59.060 --> 00:33:02.920
say that we can now require that all of the people with Lynch

553
00:33:02.980 --> 00:33:06.460
syndrome be offered national bowel cancer screening colonoscopies.

554
00:33:06.780 --> 00:33:09.340
These are the best of the best. They're very good equipment.

555
00:33:09.370 --> 00:33:10.860
They're dedicated colonoscopists.

556
00:33:11.520 --> 00:33:14.780
And they are now doing two yearly colonoscopies on all of our Lynch patients.

557
00:33:15.540 --> 00:33:19.140
In order to find those people, we've now got permission to register

558
00:33:19.540 --> 00:33:23.280
as a notifiable event, effectively, if you have Lynch syndrome in the

559
00:33:23.320 --> 00:33:25.600
National Health Service in England, and we have a

560
00:33:25.610 --> 00:33:29.020
registry in our National Disease

561
00:33:29.440 --> 00:33:33.320
Registration Service. Clare Turnbull has led a wonderful Cancer Research

562
00:33:33.380 --> 00:33:37.020
UK program, which culminated in the publication of this

563
00:33:37.040 --> 00:33:40.620
paper in 2024, where we were able to track down the

564
00:33:40.640 --> 00:33:44.320
12,292 proven carriers of Lynch syndrome who

565
00:33:44.380 --> 00:33:45.580
live in England.

566
00:33:46.540 --> 00:33:50.290
And they are now able to be tracked and of course, take part in

567
00:33:50.320 --> 00:33:53.400
research. And a paper about to appear in "Gut,"

568
00:33:53.860 --> 00:33:57.240
interestingly, will demonstrate that those who had colonoscopies more

569
00:33:57.280 --> 00:34:00.890
frequently did not have fewer colon cancers,

570
00:34:01.120 --> 00:34:02.300
something we can talk about later.

571
00:34:04.160 --> 00:34:08.160
Our contribution to this is to invent a modern-day form

572
00:34:08.220 --> 00:34:09.841
of microsatellite instability testing.

573
00:34:09.900 --> 00:34:13.660
The old five-marker test doesn't run through next-gen sequences, so

574
00:34:13.740 --> 00:34:17.321
we selected 14 highly variable ontogenic

575
00:34:17.400 --> 00:34:21.120
markers and a Bayesian calculator, which means that you don't have to do

576
00:34:21.140 --> 00:34:24.720
any hard work. You simply press the button, and if it's positive, it's

577
00:34:24.801 --> 00:34:28.660
MSI. If it's negative, it's MSS. And the nice thing is

578
00:34:28.700 --> 00:34:32.600
we've eradicated the irritating MSI load diagnoses that we had to

579
00:34:32.620 --> 00:34:36.540
deal with. The other thing is we've added in BRAF V600E, which helps target

580
00:34:36.560 --> 00:34:40.281
the ones most likely to be Lynch syndrome, and also 22 RAS

581
00:34:40.301 --> 00:34:44.180
drivers. And as of next month or the month after, we'll also add in the

582
00:34:44.220 --> 00:34:48.170
PIC3CA drivers. So you get everything in one go, one technologist,

583
00:34:48.400 --> 00:34:52.281
3,000 tumors a year, and they receive and report all of

584
00:34:52.301 --> 00:34:56.100
them. So that works very well. And it's so sensitive that we've now demonstrated

585
00:34:56.109 --> 00:34:57.880
that it will work in urine.

586
00:34:58.780 --> 00:35:02.740
And so we set up a trial regionally where we tested MSH2 gene

587
00:35:02.780 --> 00:35:06.280
carriers and found 4 of 80 of them to have an

588
00:35:06.320 --> 00:35:08.420
asymptomatic urothelial cancer.

589
00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:12.680
We've now tested more than 300. It looks like we've got about a 99%

590
00:35:12.780 --> 00:35:15.630
sensitivity and 98% specificity.

591
00:35:16.480 --> 00:35:20.370
And we're now about, with the blessing of our Cancer Research UK Early

592
00:35:20.420 --> 00:35:24.140
Detection Committee, I hope to start rolling that out nationally in

593
00:35:24.240 --> 00:35:27.920
August. And indeed, we've got our first DNA sent over from the Dana-Farber

594
00:35:28.700 --> 00:35:32.640
only last week. So that will hopefully be coming to a door near you.

595
00:35:33.960 --> 00:35:37.920
These are the people who helped develop the MSIplus assay, which

596
00:35:37.940 --> 00:35:40.700
is going to be commercially available, I have to declare, of course.

597
00:35:41.480 --> 00:35:44.640
And these are the many hundreds of people who took part in the CAPP3 trial.

598
00:35:45.340 --> 00:35:49.040
And that's of course, not to forget the 3,000 or so people with Lynch

599
00:35:49.100 --> 00:35:51.200
syndrome who made this talk possible.

600
00:35:51.560 --> 00:35:55.140
If you want to talk more about this, please come to our Cancer Prevention Research

601
00:35:55.260 --> 00:35:56.880
conference in Atlanta.

602
00:35:57.770 --> 00:36:00.299
And that's my 15 minutes finished. Thank you.

603
00:36:05.060 --> 00:36:09.020
Thanks, John. I think we'll have a panel discussion at the end and take

604
00:36:09.080 --> 00:36:10.180
questions.

605
00:36:11.120 --> 00:36:15.050
Next speaker is Nora Disis from University of Washington in

606
00:36:15.080 --> 00:36:18.500
Seattle. Nora's going to talk about vaccines for cancer

607
00:36:18.580 --> 00:36:20.200
prevention and intervention.

608
00:36:24.620 --> 00:36:25.020
Start.

609
00:36:26.960 --> 00:36:27.600
There you go.

610
00:36:27.630 --> 00:36:28.340
Thanks very much.

611
00:36:29.740 --> 00:36:30.880
These are my disclosures.

612
00:36:32.020 --> 00:36:35.880
You know, vaccines have been probably the most impactful

613
00:36:36.060 --> 00:36:38.690
intervention in human health in the last 100 years.

614
00:36:39.260 --> 00:36:43.180
If you think about it, 100 years ago, the reason why we died

615
00:36:43.220 --> 00:36:46.830
was from infectious disease. Yet the advent of

616
00:36:46.860 --> 00:36:49.794
vaccinesreally eradicated that.

617
00:36:49.984 --> 00:36:53.924
Now we die from cardiovascular disease and cancer, and

618
00:36:54.004 --> 00:36:57.564
through vaccines, we've been able to eliminate most of the

619
00:36:57.584 --> 00:37:01.344
pathogens that really reduced our

620
00:37:01.924 --> 00:37:05.804
lifespan. And the reason why this happened is because of

621
00:37:05.844 --> 00:37:08.724
the unique characteristics of vaccines.

622
00:37:09.404 --> 00:37:12.704
All vaccines induce an adaptive immune

623
00:37:12.764 --> 00:37:16.664
response, and that adaptive immune response has T

624
00:37:16.784 --> 00:37:20.384
cells and B cells that are specific to an

625
00:37:20.443 --> 00:37:24.244
antigen, an immunogenic protein that's expressed

626
00:37:24.304 --> 00:37:27.844
somewhere in the body. This makes that immune response

627
00:37:28.324 --> 00:37:32.124
very precise, selective, and most

628
00:37:32.164 --> 00:37:36.084
vaccines are associated with very little toxicity related to

629
00:37:36.124 --> 00:37:36.904
the antigen.

630
00:37:37.764 --> 00:37:41.264
T cells, now we're talking about cancer, that's the most

631
00:37:41.304 --> 00:37:44.334
important lymphocyte for tumor eradication,

632
00:37:45.284 --> 00:37:49.024
can travel anywhere in the body. So whenever that

633
00:37:49.064 --> 00:37:52.544
disease would pop up, you'll have a T cell there to recognize it.

634
00:37:53.104 --> 00:37:56.304
Because another thing the immune system generates is

635
00:37:56.364 --> 00:38:00.244
immunologic memory. That's why you can get vaccinated and 10

636
00:38:00.284 --> 00:38:04.274
years later, be exposed to a pathogen and be able to eradicate

637
00:38:04.304 --> 00:38:06.254
it before you even knew you had an exposure.

638
00:38:06.954 --> 00:38:10.924
And finally, one of the benefits of vaccines for

639
00:38:10.984 --> 00:38:14.954
cancer prevention is you can get all this with

640
00:38:15.004 --> 00:38:18.884
a limited number of exposures to the vaccine, one or two

641
00:38:18.924 --> 00:38:21.374
or three, and have lifelong immunity.

642
00:38:22.304 --> 00:38:26.104
So we're at a tipping point specifically for cancer

643
00:38:26.124 --> 00:38:29.804
vaccines targeting non-viral antigens.

644
00:38:30.244 --> 00:38:33.444
And we're at a tipping point for four reasons.

645
00:38:33.524 --> 00:38:37.444
First, we know that we need type one T cells, both CD4

646
00:38:37.484 --> 00:38:41.384
and CD8 T cells, to eradicate cancer, that

647
00:38:41.404 --> 00:38:45.264
are capable of being able to stimulate this type of response and make T

648
00:38:45.324 --> 00:38:47.524
cells that are capable of penetrating tumors.

649
00:38:48.444 --> 00:38:52.064
Further, hundreds of tumor antigens have been identified.

650
00:38:52.144 --> 00:38:54.464
Mutated antigens, shared antigens.

651
00:38:54.864 --> 00:38:58.504
You can literally tailor-make a cancer vaccine for any tumor.

652
00:38:59.184 --> 00:39:01.824
We have very safe and effective vaccine

653
00:39:02.984 --> 00:39:06.664
delivery technologies, which are nucleic acid-based.

654
00:39:07.264 --> 00:39:11.013
And we're really dealing with more appropriate patient populations.

655
00:39:11.584 --> 00:39:15.524
When you go back to infectious disease, there isn't any infectious

656
00:39:15.624 --> 00:39:18.624
disease vaccine you'd use to actually treat cancer.

657
00:39:19.784 --> 00:39:23.584
And as we see more successes or

658
00:39:23.624 --> 00:39:26.793
inklings of success in terms of therapeutic vaccines,

659
00:39:27.384 --> 00:39:30.194
vaccines have moved more and more into the prevention setting.

660
00:39:30.654 --> 00:39:33.793
And what I'm going to show you today are clinical trials that are

661
00:39:33.884 --> 00:39:37.864
ongoing of cancer vaccines in the prevention setting.

662
00:39:38.444 --> 00:39:40.384
And there are three ways we do this.

663
00:39:41.364 --> 00:39:44.924
We use vaccines for interception of

664
00:39:45.064 --> 00:39:48.824
pre-invasive lesions. Now, this is the

665
00:39:48.884 --> 00:39:51.744
highest bar. It's a therapeutic vaccine.

666
00:39:52.164 --> 00:39:55.924
You're immunizing someone with a disease to make that

667
00:39:55.934 --> 00:39:59.164
disease go away. Next, you have the

668
00:39:59.224 --> 00:40:03.044
classic way that we immunize. That's primary

669
00:40:03.084 --> 00:40:06.064
prevention, prophylaxis, immunizing

670
00:40:06.074 --> 00:40:10.024
patients that have never had cancer, but probably are

671
00:40:10.064 --> 00:40:13.764
at high risk. And then the final topic I want to

672
00:40:13.804 --> 00:40:17.784
introduce very briefly is the idea of vaccination to

673
00:40:17.844 --> 00:40:21.744
reduce cancer risk, and this is a new area

674
00:40:21.784 --> 00:40:25.644
of vaccines. And what I have here is a list of tumors

675
00:40:26.004 --> 00:40:29.984
with well-defined, pre-invasive

676
00:40:30.044 --> 00:40:32.724
lesions, well-defined high-risk groups.

677
00:40:33.144 --> 00:40:37.064
And you can find a preventive cancer vaccine for almost

678
00:40:37.184 --> 00:40:39.083
every tumor on this slide.

679
00:40:40.084 --> 00:40:41.924
So let's start with interception.

680
00:40:42.564 --> 00:40:46.324
Probably the first clinical trials for cancer

681
00:40:46.344 --> 00:40:50.064
interception took place for ductal carcinoma in situ.

682
00:40:51.024 --> 00:40:54.664
DCIS, very common, accounts for 20% of all breast

683
00:40:54.704 --> 00:40:56.334
cancer diagnoses.

684
00:40:57.204 --> 00:41:00.984
But only 10% to 15% of DCIS will develop invasive

685
00:41:01.044 --> 00:41:03.644
cancer if you leave them untreated.

686
00:41:03.684 --> 00:41:07.384
The problem is that when they do develop invasive

687
00:41:07.464 --> 00:41:11.444
cancer, they don't always come back locally, they can come back systemically.

688
00:41:12.384 --> 00:41:15.584
So surgery and radiation, which we use to treat DCIS,

689
00:41:15.964 --> 00:41:19.784
prevent local recurrence, but may not necessarily improve

690
00:41:19.844 --> 00:41:23.764
overall survival because of that coming

691
00:41:23.804 --> 00:41:27.764
back as a systemic disease. Now, 30% to 40% of

692
00:41:27.804 --> 00:41:31.704
DCIS overexpress the protein HER2, which

693
00:41:31.744 --> 00:41:35.704
is a well-known tumor antigen in breast cancer, and it also happens

694
00:41:35.764 --> 00:41:39.524
to be associated with an increased risk of progression to

695
00:41:39.564 --> 00:41:42.664
invasive breast cancer from DCIS.

696
00:41:43.704 --> 00:41:46.984
Brian Susnik at UPenn was the first to really

697
00:41:47.024 --> 00:41:50.774
vaccinate patients to try to eradicate DCIS, and

698
00:41:50.804 --> 00:41:54.584
he did it with a very early study of a small number of patients,

699
00:41:55.164 --> 00:41:58.864
giving them their own autologous dendritic cells loaded with

700
00:41:58.884 --> 00:42:02.444
HER2/neu epitopes internodally to make

701
00:42:02.524 --> 00:42:06.004
sure that these antigens went directly to the lymph nodes to

702
00:42:06.024 --> 00:42:09.904
stimulate the T cells in kind of a window of opportunity study

703
00:42:09.944 --> 00:42:11.674
before they had definitive surgery.

704
00:42:12.214 --> 00:42:14.224
And he showed two important concepts.

705
00:42:14.384 --> 00:42:14.884
First,

706
00:42:15.944 --> 00:42:19.644
the vaccines induced very significant levels of type one T

707
00:42:19.724 --> 00:42:23.324
cells and antibodies. But secondly, seven of the

708
00:42:23.344 --> 00:42:27.044
11 evaluable patients actually lost expression of

709
00:42:27.084 --> 00:42:30.504
HER2/neu on their DCIS, so they eliminated the

710
00:42:30.564 --> 00:42:31.124
target,

711
00:42:32.024 --> 00:42:35.924
and he saw T cells involved in the DCIS.

712
00:42:36.704 --> 00:42:40.074
He subsequently went on to expand these studies and showed

713
00:42:40.124 --> 00:42:44.024
that he could generate pathologic complete responses

714
00:42:44.444 --> 00:42:48.224
in about 30% of DCIS patients that were

715
00:42:48.244 --> 00:42:51.164
HER2/neu positive and estrogen receptor negative.

716
00:42:51.764 --> 00:42:55.584
And now many others are using HER2/neu-based vaccines

717
00:42:55.844 --> 00:42:59.624
to treat DCIS. There's a clinical trial of a MUC1

718
00:42:59.684 --> 00:43:03.474
vaccine to treat DCIS, and a multi-antigen

719
00:43:03.484 --> 00:43:07.404
vaccine that will hit both ER positive and ER negative

720
00:43:07.784 --> 00:43:09.384
LCIS and DCIS

721
00:43:10.324 --> 00:43:12.984
is about to enter clinical trials in this

722
00:43:13.044 --> 00:43:16.536
area.So how would you develop a

723
00:43:16.576 --> 00:43:20.396
prophylactic vaccine where you didn't have the tumor,

724
00:43:20.836 --> 00:43:23.036
and you couldn't pick the antigens from the tumor?

725
00:43:23.656 --> 00:43:27.556
Well, one way is to look at patients who are genetic high risk

726
00:43:27.576 --> 00:43:31.486
and try to find commonalities of the tumors that

727
00:43:31.516 --> 00:43:35.436
they develop. And so, a study that was just published,

728
00:43:35.496 --> 00:43:39.196
which was quite interesting, was prophylactic vaccination for

729
00:43:39.296 --> 00:43:42.886
Lynch syndrome, most common cause of inherited colon and

730
00:43:42.936 --> 00:43:44.216
endometrial cancer,

731
00:43:45.376 --> 00:43:47.456
younger age and multiple cancers.

732
00:43:47.636 --> 00:43:51.496
And the type of pathologic variants in the MMR

733
00:43:51.716 --> 00:43:55.556
repair genes that you just heard about really dictate where

734
00:43:55.636 --> 00:43:59.296
that cancer's going to come up, so very difficult to screen for.

735
00:44:00.216 --> 00:44:03.036
And the risk varies by mutation.

736
00:44:04.636 --> 00:44:08.516
So one of the commonalities in this group

737
00:44:08.576 --> 00:44:12.056
of tumors when they arise is that they develop frameshift

738
00:44:12.156 --> 00:44:16.016
mutations. And it was shown by a group in the Netherlands that

739
00:44:16.056 --> 00:44:19.976
these frameshift mutations are immunogenic and can act

740
00:44:20.016 --> 00:44:23.996
as neoantigens. And they can be predicted and used in vaccines,

741
00:44:24.056 --> 00:44:28.016
and they have been for about a decade in terms of looking at

742
00:44:28.076 --> 00:44:31.636
a person's particular mutation and trying to

743
00:44:31.716 --> 00:44:35.116
tailor-make precision vaccines for that individual

744
00:44:35.256 --> 00:44:35.736
patient.

745
00:44:36.676 --> 00:44:40.516
But Eduardo Villar Sanchez headed a study, it was

746
00:44:40.576 --> 00:44:44.196
just published in "Nature Medicine," where a vaccine called

747
00:44:44.256 --> 00:44:47.976
NAUS209 took 209

748
00:44:48.056 --> 00:44:51.596
frameshift mutations, so this vaccine could be off the

749
00:44:51.676 --> 00:44:55.316
shelf. And what they did is they put them in viral

750
00:44:55.336 --> 00:44:59.176
vectors. One was a great ape adenovirus,

751
00:44:59.496 --> 00:45:02.916
so something your immune system had never seen before, it would be very foreign.

752
00:45:03.676 --> 00:45:07.136
And the boost vaccine was with a modified Ankara

753
00:45:08.236 --> 00:45:11.976
virus, so the two did not neutralize each other.

754
00:45:12.636 --> 00:45:15.866
Forty-five people were enrolled, subjects with Lynch syndrome,

755
00:45:16.456 --> 00:45:19.316
high-grade dysplasia, cervical cancer they did not have.

756
00:45:19.376 --> 00:45:22.606
So these were people right, walking in off the door.

757
00:45:23.176 --> 00:45:26.406
And the primary endpoints of the study were safety and

758
00:45:26.456 --> 00:45:30.196
immunogenicity. They had an 8%

759
00:45:30.436 --> 00:45:34.336
grade 3 adverse event rate, which was really related to the

760
00:45:34.376 --> 00:45:38.176
first immunization, the priming immunization with that great ape

761
00:45:38.216 --> 00:45:42.126
vaccine. And afterwards, they had

762
00:45:42.196 --> 00:45:46.116
very few adverse events. And the adverse events were very similar to what you'd see

763
00:45:46.156 --> 00:45:49.416
with any vaccine, headache, fatigue, nausea,

764
00:45:49.516 --> 00:45:50.176
myalgia.

765
00:45:51.316 --> 00:45:54.776
And most interestingly, 100% of the

766
00:45:54.796 --> 00:45:58.556
patients developed immunity to some of the frameshift

767
00:45:58.656 --> 00:46:02.106
mutations. And in fact, the immunity

768
00:46:02.316 --> 00:46:05.176
persisted in the vast majority,

769
00:46:05.386 --> 00:46:08.936
85% over a year, after just a single

770
00:46:08.976 --> 00:46:11.326
prime and a single boost immunization.

771
00:46:12.126 --> 00:46:15.856
That's really great immunogenicity of this approach.

772
00:46:16.416 --> 00:46:20.296
And when you look at that pink circle, they had so many antigens,

773
00:46:20.356 --> 00:46:24.276
they had to test them in pools. You can see most of the

774
00:46:24.316 --> 00:46:28.296
patients were responding to multiple antigens in those

775
00:46:28.336 --> 00:46:32.236
pools. So this highly immunogenic vaccine will be

776
00:46:32.256 --> 00:46:36.176
moving on to phase two studies to really look at cancer prevention.

777
00:46:37.116 --> 00:46:40.416
The final couple of slides I want to show you is the concept of

778
00:46:40.436 --> 00:46:43.736
reducing cancer risk by

779
00:46:44.276 --> 00:46:47.076
quelling or quenching chronic inflammation.

780
00:46:47.486 --> 00:46:50.966
And chronic inflammation is a common cause of many cancers.

781
00:46:51.036 --> 00:46:54.335
About 30% of cancers can be linked to chronic

782
00:46:54.396 --> 00:46:58.176
inflammation. And one of the places where we see type one

783
00:46:58.236 --> 00:47:01.706
inflammation commonly is in metabolic obesity,

784
00:47:02.296 --> 00:47:06.236
where hypertrophic adipocytes cause

785
00:47:06.256 --> 00:47:09.996
metabolic stress, create a microenvironment that's very

786
00:47:10.056 --> 00:47:13.936
favorable to activating innate immune cells and

787
00:47:13.976 --> 00:47:16.136
making them antigen-presenting cells.

788
00:47:16.166 --> 00:47:19.576
And the proteins within the adipocytes become

789
00:47:19.676 --> 00:47:22.936
abnormal and highly upregulated, and they actually act as

790
00:47:23.076 --> 00:47:26.716
antigens. And what happens is you get antigen

791
00:47:26.756 --> 00:47:29.576
presentation, you get an adaptive immune response.

792
00:47:29.986 --> 00:47:33.636
That environment makes that continue, accelerates it,

793
00:47:34.096 --> 00:47:37.536
and you're fighting for nutrients. You create metabolic dysfunction.

794
00:47:37.596 --> 00:47:39.496
The T cells become dysfunctional.

795
00:47:39.926 --> 00:47:43.556
They can't immune surveil. When the cancer comes up, you

796
00:47:43.616 --> 00:47:47.286
eventually develop EMT, and you end up with

797
00:47:47.356 --> 00:47:47.866
cancer.

798
00:47:49.136 --> 00:47:53.086
Our group's been working on type one selective vaccines, but

799
00:47:53.116 --> 00:47:57.096
we've also begun to create anti-inflammatory vaccines.

800
00:47:57.536 --> 00:48:00.876
And we identified many of these upregulated proteins found in

801
00:48:00.896 --> 00:48:04.746
adipocytes and created a vaccine directed to about

802
00:48:04.836 --> 00:48:08.626
six of these proteins called adipocyte-directed

803
00:48:08.696 --> 00:48:12.436
vaccines, that specifically elicits T cells that

804
00:48:12.556 --> 00:48:16.156
secrete high levels of IL-10, IL-4, and

805
00:48:16.216 --> 00:48:19.576
IL-5. So you can see, going back to precision

806
00:48:19.676 --> 00:48:22.296
prevention, being able to directly

807
00:48:23.996 --> 00:48:27.956
target these vaccines where the inflammation is

808
00:48:28.156 --> 00:48:29.196
in the adipocytes.

809
00:48:30.436 --> 00:48:33.916
And I'll just end up with this slide of two models of this

810
00:48:33.956 --> 00:48:37.096
adipocyte-directed vaccine. One is

811
00:48:37.236 --> 00:48:40.816
in diabetes, the diabetes

812
00:48:40.896 --> 00:48:44.716
model of obesity, and the other is in a model

813
00:48:44.916 --> 00:48:48.706
of breast cancer, the TgMMTV-PyM mouse, that

814
00:48:48.756 --> 00:48:52.716
when you make these animals obese, they develop their breast cancers more quickly,

815
00:48:52.736 --> 00:48:55.616
and they develop multifocal breast cancers.

816
00:48:55.656 --> 00:48:59.536
You can see in this model, when you start feeding them a high-fat diet

817
00:48:59.656 --> 00:49:03.076
at 10 weeks, they become obese, and then we

818
00:49:03.176 --> 00:49:06.820
vaccinate them with this adipocyte vaccine.The

819
00:49:06.900 --> 00:49:10.720
Advac vaccine compared to the sham vaccine control

820
00:49:10.780 --> 00:49:14.540
really reduces the amount of CD8 T cells that are found in the

821
00:49:14.560 --> 00:49:18.100
visceral fat. These CD8 T cells are what's

822
00:49:18.110 --> 00:49:21.080
driving this immune proliferation.

823
00:49:21.110 --> 00:49:24.940
And you can see we're getting to the point where we're correcting it

824
00:49:24.980 --> 00:49:28.520
nearly to lean. What you'd like to see in normal fat

825
00:49:28.880 --> 00:49:32.800
are high levels of T regulatory cells, and you can see

826
00:49:32.820 --> 00:49:36.700
in Advac immunized animals, their T regulatory

827
00:49:36.760 --> 00:49:40.700
cell level in the visceral fat is coming back to what you'd see

828
00:49:40.740 --> 00:49:44.300
in lean. And finally, these animals develop insulin

829
00:49:44.340 --> 00:49:48.140
insensitivity and frank diabetes, and you can see compared

830
00:49:48.180 --> 00:49:51.820
to sham vaccine versus Advac, we're beginning to

831
00:49:51.880 --> 00:49:55.670
correct their ability to handle their glucose and

832
00:49:55.670 --> 00:49:57.850
changing that insulin insensitivity.

833
00:49:58.520 --> 00:50:02.380
And here in the FEB-new mice, you can see in the

834
00:50:02.440 --> 00:50:06.260
same model, this time going out a much longer time, that

835
00:50:06.270 --> 00:50:10.160
animals that become obese and have the sham vaccine

836
00:50:10.259 --> 00:50:14.240
all develop tumors by 30 weeks. Animals who get the Advac

837
00:50:14.300 --> 00:50:18.160
vaccine, 60% of them are still tumor-free at 30

838
00:50:18.260 --> 00:50:21.920
weeks, and they've reduced their leptin levels, which are

839
00:50:22.000 --> 00:50:25.320
associated with the EMT transformation.

840
00:50:26.760 --> 00:50:30.640
So finally, I think in the next few years, we're rapidly going to be

841
00:50:30.780 --> 00:50:33.999
seeing more vaccines coming in for cancer prevention.

842
00:50:34.040 --> 00:50:35.960
They're already in the clinic right now.

843
00:50:36.170 --> 00:50:38.100
They're already in phase two studies.

844
00:50:38.630 --> 00:50:42.600
And I think it's important as we team up with trying to define

845
00:50:42.700 --> 00:50:46.220
what is high risk and what are the levels of high risk,

846
00:50:46.670 --> 00:50:50.360
there will be vaccines for people at every level, vaccines to

847
00:50:50.400 --> 00:50:53.660
prevent disease recurrence, vaccines to treat

848
00:50:53.700 --> 00:50:57.680
interception for those who have high-risk lesions, frank

849
00:50:57.820 --> 00:51:01.480
prophylactic vaccines for people who've never had cancer,

850
00:51:02.100 --> 00:51:05.760
and risk-reducing vaccines, not only directed against chronic

851
00:51:05.820 --> 00:51:08.720
inflammation, but other risk factors for cancer.

852
00:51:09.640 --> 00:51:09.960
Thank you.

853
00:51:15.719 --> 00:51:18.880
Thanks, Nora. Our last speaker in this session is

854
00:51:19.420 --> 00:51:22.320
Joanne Elmore from UCLA School of Medicine.

855
00:51:22.760 --> 00:51:26.430
She's going to speak about AI in cancer diagnosis, promise and

856
00:51:26.480 --> 00:51:27.160
performance,

857
00:51:28.060 --> 00:51:29.420
and the human AI factor.

858
00:51:31.680 --> 00:51:35.170
And my goal is to have you develop a healthy

859
00:51:35.320 --> 00:51:37.040
skepticism about AI.

860
00:51:42.880 --> 00:51:46.700
My talk will emphasize two areas where we need to do better,

861
00:51:47.760 --> 00:51:49.020
and I think AI can help.

862
00:51:49.880 --> 00:51:53.260
Then I'm going to quickly go over some examples of AI work, but talk

863
00:51:53.340 --> 00:51:57.040
about challenges. And then I want to conclude with the

864
00:51:57.060 --> 00:52:01.040
important and understudied topic of the human

865
00:52:01.140 --> 00:52:02.160
AI interaction.

866
00:52:02.980 --> 00:52:04.140
These are my disclosures.

867
00:52:05.440 --> 00:52:06.200
Starting with

868
00:52:07.220 --> 00:52:11.000
the first area that I think AI can help us, risk prediction models.

869
00:52:12.590 --> 00:52:16.280
They work really well at a population, but not so

870
00:52:16.320 --> 00:52:18.980
well at the individual patient level.

871
00:52:20.500 --> 00:52:22.500
Years ago, I asked the following question.

872
00:52:23.120 --> 00:52:27.040
For example, breast cancer risk models, how well do they work

873
00:52:27.080 --> 00:52:30.880
in categorizing individual women as average versus high

874
00:52:30.920 --> 00:52:34.380
risk for developing invasive breast cancer? I'm an internist.

875
00:52:34.480 --> 00:52:35.820
I use the models in my clinic.

876
00:52:36.680 --> 00:52:40.640
I took three commonly used models, used every day in the US

877
00:52:40.680 --> 00:52:44.380
and internationally. I applied them to the same 31,000 women.

878
00:52:44.420 --> 00:52:46.040
I estimated five-year risk.

879
00:52:47.000 --> 00:52:50.580
As you would guess, they worked great at the accuracy at the

880
00:52:50.640 --> 00:52:53.640
population level, discrimination, calibration.

881
00:52:53.960 --> 00:52:55.440
This is what's commonly reported.

882
00:52:56.040 --> 00:52:59.560
And I found that more than 21% of the women were classified as high

883
00:52:59.660 --> 00:53:01.580
risk by all three models.

884
00:53:02.720 --> 00:53:03.020
But

885
00:53:04.660 --> 00:53:07.680
let me show you the Venn diagram of all of the women that were

886
00:53:07.740 --> 00:53:10.690
identified by at least one model.

887
00:53:12.810 --> 00:53:13.880
Not much overlap.

888
00:53:15.920 --> 00:53:19.460
These are our current actively used risk prediction models.

889
00:53:19.900 --> 00:53:23.300
What does this mean clinically? It means if I'm in clinic and I

890
00:53:23.660 --> 00:53:27.480
use one risk model on one woman, another risk model on the second woman,

891
00:53:28.160 --> 00:53:31.000
I may share with them different comments and different

892
00:53:31.040 --> 00:53:33.340
recommendations.

893
00:53:34.640 --> 00:53:38.610
The second area that we have a challenge, but

894
00:53:38.640 --> 00:53:41.160
where I hope AI can help, is in diagnostic

895
00:53:41.240 --> 00:53:44.240
accuracy. An earlier study,

896
00:53:46.180 --> 00:53:47.720
I took mammograms

897
00:53:48.560 --> 00:53:52.020
and asked radiologists to independently interpret them.

898
00:53:52.060 --> 00:53:54.020
These weren't medical students or residents.

899
00:53:54.040 --> 00:53:56.840
These were actively practicing radiologists.

900
00:53:57.510 --> 00:54:00.440
They gave me different interpretations.

901
00:54:00.520 --> 00:54:04.150
You can see the range here. Now, this is just a single case, but in this

902
00:54:04.260 --> 00:54:07.680
study, I showed them 150

903
00:54:07.740 --> 00:54:08.460
mammograms.

904
00:54:09.720 --> 00:54:13.300
I could, in the paper, report Kappa statistics, et cetera, but to me,

905
00:54:13.360 --> 00:54:16.130
clinically, if one radiologist says,

906
00:54:17.000 --> 00:54:20.620
"Routine follow-up in a year or two," and the other says, "Get a biopsy," that's

907
00:54:20.660 --> 00:54:24.430
clinically significant. That happened in 25% of these cases.

908
00:54:25.520 --> 00:54:29.360
Now, I realized I was actually assuming if they recommended a biopsy,

909
00:54:29.420 --> 00:54:33.120
they were recommending it in the same breast, but women have two breasts,

910
00:54:33.260 --> 00:54:35.620
and that happened in 9% of the cases.

911
00:54:37.540 --> 00:54:41.380
I spent about 10 years studying human decision-making of

912
00:54:41.420 --> 00:54:45.330
radiologists, and I'm going to share a personal story of how I

913
00:54:46.340 --> 00:54:49.260
and why I transitioned to pathology.

914
00:54:51.780 --> 00:54:55.420
My dermatologist called me late on a Friday night and said, "Joanne,

915
00:54:56.140 --> 00:54:58.590
I hate calling patients with this kind of news, but..."

916
00:54:59.540 --> 00:55:01.660
And I'm a physician. I knew what that meant.

917
00:55:01.760 --> 00:55:04.840
I, in a skin biopsy, had invasive

918
00:55:04.880 --> 00:55:08.552
melanoma.We obtained a second opinion on the

919
00:55:08.592 --> 00:55:12.052
pathology, and they said, "Oh, no, it's benign." So then we sent it to a third

920
00:55:12.092 --> 00:55:15.992
pathologist who said, "Oh, it's just a complicated Spitz lesion." And I

921
00:55:16.092 --> 00:55:19.432
realized all of my prior research

922
00:55:19.852 --> 00:55:23.752
in radiology had been based on the outcome of cancer,

923
00:55:23.852 --> 00:55:26.982
yes or no. And I thought, "I need to study this."

924
00:55:28.112 --> 00:55:31.652
So we did. We recruited US pathologists,

925
00:55:31.772 --> 00:55:33.062
actively practicing,

926
00:55:33.952 --> 00:55:36.372
and had them interpret cases independently.

927
00:55:36.772 --> 00:55:39.292
We've done this in breast and in skin biopsies.

928
00:55:39.872 --> 00:55:43.532
Our gold standard, we recruited world experts.

929
00:55:43.892 --> 00:55:44.212
And

930
00:55:45.072 --> 00:55:49.012
on the topic, they independently interpreted the cases and came

931
00:55:49.072 --> 00:55:51.492
up with our reference consensus diagnosis.

932
00:55:51.572 --> 00:55:54.092
But I will admit it was a bit like a Mad Hatter

933
00:55:55.072 --> 00:55:57.732
tea party. And let me share the results with you.

934
00:55:58.132 --> 00:56:02.012
This is just one skin biopsy case. The glass slide

935
00:56:02.052 --> 00:56:05.432
was sent around the US, and 36 pathologists

936
00:56:05.592 --> 00:56:08.972
kindly participated because they care about this.

937
00:56:09.012 --> 00:56:12.912
They want us to do better. Look at the variability, though.

938
00:56:12.932 --> 00:56:15.252
They're all looking at the same glass slide.

939
00:56:15.432 --> 00:56:19.042
Only 10 agreed with the consensus of the

940
00:56:19.212 --> 00:56:19.832
experts.

941
00:56:21.492 --> 00:56:24.872
This is only one case. This shows you the results for

942
00:56:25.092 --> 00:56:29.012
240 cases, 187 pathologists,

943
00:56:29.432 --> 00:56:32.852
almost 9,000 interpretations. The Y-axis is the

944
00:56:33.832 --> 00:56:36.112
percent concordance with the reference.

945
00:56:36.272 --> 00:56:39.182
You could say it's accuracy if you trust our reference.

946
00:56:40.112 --> 00:56:43.852
On the X-axis, you'll see the class one cases that the

947
00:56:43.912 --> 00:56:47.252
experts called benign. Pretty much the US

948
00:56:47.332 --> 00:56:51.212
pathologists agree. But look on the far right, the invasive melanomas.

949
00:56:52.592 --> 00:56:56.522
More than 20% of the time, US pathologists were downgrading

950
00:56:56.692 --> 00:56:57.772
and misclassifying.

951
00:57:00.492 --> 00:57:04.442
Now, one part of our design was that it was

952
00:57:04.472 --> 00:57:07.052
two phases. We took the same cases.

953
00:57:07.252 --> 00:57:08.832
They interpreted them in phase one.

954
00:57:08.952 --> 00:57:11.332
We gave them a six-month washout period.

955
00:57:11.832 --> 00:57:15.252
We renumbered them and sent them to the same pathologist.

956
00:57:15.852 --> 00:57:19.832
So the question is: will they give the same diagnosis?

957
00:57:20.712 --> 00:57:23.832
If they would, it would all be at 100% when you're

958
00:57:23.872 --> 00:57:26.672
