00:58:45.472 --> 00:58:48.612
The red arrows point to the accuracy of

980
00:58:48.621 --> 00:58:51.372
pathologists interpreting cases, their

981
00:58:51.382 --> 00:58:55.272
sensitivity/specificity. And then this shows the results

982
00:58:55.312 --> 00:58:58.942
of two AI models. One's called a tissue distribution

983
00:58:59.032 --> 00:59:02.252
feature. The other is based on structure.

984
00:59:02.272 --> 00:59:03.892
But I want to point out how old this is.

985
00:59:03.932 --> 00:59:07.872
This was published seven years ago, and we were already doing well

986
00:59:07.952 --> 00:59:10.972
then. Think what's happened just in the last months with AI.

987
00:59:12.652 --> 00:59:16.572
Currently, I'm taking the image data shown here on the top left,

988
00:59:16.962 --> 00:59:19.952
merging it with text data, the clinical words

989
00:59:20.012 --> 00:59:23.642
around the images, and we're looking at survival

990
00:59:23.792 --> 00:59:27.732
estimation. And what I like is that I don't understand the black

991
00:59:27.812 --> 00:59:31.592
box, so I'm having the AI give me words to explain

992
00:59:31.692 --> 00:59:34.772
why it's calling someone high risk versus low risk.

993
00:59:35.172 --> 00:59:38.892
We're also adding in a pathologist, a human in the

994
00:59:38.932 --> 00:59:42.192
loop, so that we can further understand the black box.

995
00:59:43.352 --> 00:59:43.492
Now,

996
00:59:44.792 --> 00:59:48.692
most importantly are a few areas that are challenges

997
00:59:48.732 --> 00:59:51.612
in AI model development. The first is the gold

998
00:59:51.792 --> 00:59:55.552
standard. When our statistician saw the amount

999
00:59:55.592 --> 00:59:59.492
of diagnostic variability in a diagnosis of cancer, her first comment

1000
00:59:59.572 --> 00:59:59.722
was,

1001
01:00:00.602 --> 01:00:02.402
"Should we have had five experts,

1002
01:00:03.492 --> 01:00:07.432
or should we have had seven?" And basically, the outcome of the

1003
01:00:07.572 --> 01:00:11.422
woman, the clinical outcome, is what's most important, but once you've removed

1004
01:00:11.432 --> 01:00:14.302
a tissue, you might have changed the underlying

1005
01:00:14.392 --> 01:00:18.372
biology. And I think we're still struggling with the gold standard

1006
01:00:18.432 --> 01:00:18.872
outcome.

1007
01:00:20.832 --> 01:00:24.132
Second, the black box transparency.

1008
01:00:24.892 --> 01:00:28.312
If we don't understand it, as clinicians, will we trust it?

1009
01:00:30.192 --> 01:00:33.172
Third is so important, bias and generalizability.

1010
01:00:33.332 --> 01:00:35.052
I want to share a slide.

1011
01:00:36.212 --> 01:00:36.652
First of all,

1012
01:00:37.752 --> 01:00:41.592
this is an example on the left of an AI program that was built

1013
01:00:41.602 --> 01:00:45.232
to detect skin conditions. It worked quite well,

1014
01:00:45.272 --> 01:00:47.212
but as the authors pointed out,

1015
01:00:48.092 --> 01:00:51.712
a limitation was that their data in didn't include all skin

1016
01:00:51.772 --> 01:00:54.852
types. We need to make certain that our data

1017
01:00:55.732 --> 01:00:56.952
is generalizable.

1018
01:01:00.872 --> 01:01:04.792
A poignant example on the right was published in "Science," and this

1019
01:01:04.832 --> 01:01:08.580
one really bothers me. There's a lot of-bias in our health

1020
01:01:08.660 --> 01:01:11.160
data, and these authors

1021
01:01:12.160 --> 01:01:14.320
studied an algorithm that was

1022
01:01:15.200 --> 01:01:19.140
actively being used in US hospitals.

1023
01:01:20.260 --> 01:01:23.780
And this AI model was systematically

1024
01:01:23.840 --> 01:01:26.100
discriminating against black patients.

1025
01:01:28.260 --> 01:01:32.150
And the reason is that the bias in the model occurred because

1026
01:01:32.150 --> 01:01:35.880
the algorithm, it used health costs as a

1027
01:01:35.900 --> 01:01:37.540
proxy for health needs.

1028
01:01:39.400 --> 01:01:42.850
We need to assure that the development of AI tools

1029
01:01:42.980 --> 01:01:46.620
includes multidisciplinary teams, not silos,

1030
01:01:46.940 --> 01:01:48.620
and we need to be very cautious.

1031
01:01:51.180 --> 01:01:53.540
This brings me to my third area,

1032
01:01:54.520 --> 01:01:58.100
which is the human-computer interface, and

1033
01:01:59.480 --> 01:02:01.500
I don't feel like this is getting enough attention.

1034
01:02:02.360 --> 01:02:05.900
We humans don't always react and interact with computers the

1035
01:02:05.940 --> 01:02:09.860
way you think we would. And I'm going to explain why I'm interested

1036
01:02:09.920 --> 01:02:10.260
in this.

1037
01:02:11.200 --> 01:02:14.680
I worked at a county hospital, and one of my patients

1038
01:02:14.960 --> 01:02:15.940
asked me in clinic,

1039
01:02:16.760 --> 01:02:20.750
"Why are they charging me $45 for this extra computer thing on

1040
01:02:20.780 --> 01:02:24.730
my screening mammogram?" She was working two jobs, and I

1041
01:02:24.740 --> 01:02:26.400
thought it was a valid question.

1042
01:02:27.560 --> 01:02:30.600
At the time, I was working with the Breast Cancer Surveillance Consortium.

1043
01:02:30.640 --> 01:02:34.290
We had access to hundreds of thousands of screening mammograms,

1044
01:02:35.040 --> 01:02:38.740
and I looked, and I saw, oh, half had been interpreted with a computer-aided

1045
01:02:38.750 --> 01:02:40.860
detection program. The other half hadn't.

1046
01:02:41.740 --> 01:02:45.220
Let me see how much benefit we were

1047
01:02:45.280 --> 01:02:49.040
getting from that early computer-aided

1048
01:02:49.050 --> 01:02:51.120
detection program on screening mammograms.

1049
01:02:52.240 --> 01:02:54.600
This shows you the results. Simple ROC curve.

1050
01:02:55.020 --> 01:02:58.540
Black line at the top is the results for the hundreds of thousands of screening

1051
01:02:58.620 --> 01:03:02.120
exams with no computer use. Red dashed line,

1052
01:03:03.080 --> 01:03:04.880
results when the computer was used.

1053
01:03:06.980 --> 01:03:08.340
When the computer was used,

1054
01:03:09.540 --> 01:03:12.760
it was associated with significantly

1055
01:03:13.400 --> 01:03:13.820
lower

1056
01:03:14.740 --> 01:03:15.500
accuracy.

1057
01:03:17.140 --> 01:03:17.720
Not good.

1058
01:03:19.780 --> 01:03:23.640
After this publication, others reproduced the same,

1059
01:03:24.540 --> 01:03:26.820
and it didn't really change practice.

1060
01:03:27.420 --> 01:03:30.250
It was a moneymaker for many facilities, and

1061
01:03:31.260 --> 01:03:35.020
90%-plus of all mammograms were

1062
01:03:35.140 --> 01:03:38.260
using this older computer-aided detection program.

1063
01:03:38.760 --> 01:03:41.240
So this could've been harming patients.

1064
01:03:42.020 --> 01:03:42.260
Let me

1065
01:03:44.160 --> 01:03:48.020
discuss some hypotheses and some potential reasons why we

1066
01:03:48.080 --> 01:03:51.300
may have found that the computer was leading to harm.

1067
01:03:52.880 --> 01:03:55.600
First is automation bias.

1068
01:03:56.400 --> 01:03:59.700
Clinician may just want to go with whatever the AI says.

1069
01:04:00.960 --> 01:04:04.690
Radiologists care. They don't want to miss a cancer,

1070
01:04:05.180 --> 01:04:09.020
so if the computer marks an area, they may be hesitant to

1071
01:04:09.060 --> 01:04:12.660
not call the woman back for additional testing. The recall rate might go up.

1072
01:04:14.540 --> 01:04:15.080
Secondly,

1073
01:04:16.500 --> 01:04:20.210
we all get tired sometimes in the afternoon, and if

1074
01:04:20.260 --> 01:04:24.230
the computer program doesn't flag anything, maybe you'll assume it has your

1075
01:04:24.260 --> 01:04:26.380
back, and you may miss things.

1076
01:04:27.330 --> 01:04:30.360
We need to be cautious with this. Secondly,

1077
01:04:30.980 --> 01:04:31.700
de-skilling.

1078
01:04:32.780 --> 01:04:36.260
I'm very worried about de-skilling of our next generation of physicians.

1079
01:04:36.600 --> 01:04:40.420
All of the med students are using AI to help them figure

1080
01:04:40.500 --> 01:04:42.200
out a diagnosis.

1081
01:04:43.460 --> 01:04:46.400
I want to share with you that when I was typing notes for this talk,

1082
01:04:47.400 --> 01:04:51.100
there was an autocorrect when I typed de-skilling.

1083
01:04:52.380 --> 01:04:54.790
Doctors killing was what was typed.

1084
01:04:55.660 --> 01:04:58.580
It may be an overstatement, but it is a real concern to me.

1085
01:04:59.100 --> 01:05:01.180
And the final is the intent.

1086
01:05:02.580 --> 01:05:06.420
There's a lot of rah-rah AI, but is it

1087
01:05:06.460 --> 01:05:09.260
going to help our patients? We care.

1088
01:05:09.620 --> 01:05:10.560
We want it to help.

1089
01:05:12.960 --> 01:05:16.060
On that point, I'm involved in two ongoing studies.

1090
01:05:16.180 --> 01:05:20.160
The first is a prospective randomized trial

1091
01:05:20.200 --> 01:05:24.070
of AI in screening mammography called the PRISM Trial, funded by

1092
01:05:24.100 --> 01:05:27.380
PCORI, and we're testing the real-world

1093
01:05:27.560 --> 01:05:31.260
impact. The AI tool is Transpara by ScreenPoint

1094
01:05:31.320 --> 01:05:34.100
Medical. And the exams are being

1095
01:05:34.200 --> 01:05:37.900
randomized via a platform from Aidoc,

1096
01:05:38.060 --> 01:05:42.040
either to show the radiologist, "Here's an exam with AI" versus

1097
01:05:42.120 --> 01:05:45.960
just read the exam without. Our target enrollment is 400,000,

1098
01:05:46.080 --> 01:05:46.900
and we're already

1099
01:05:48.060 --> 01:05:49.960
accruing. We're at about 40,000 now.

1100
01:05:52.240 --> 01:05:55.920
Second study I'm involved in is a bit more granular on

1101
01:05:56.000 --> 01:05:59.160
the how clinicians are interacting with the AI.

1102
01:05:59.550 --> 01:06:03.400
I'm looking at topics such as what kind of AI

1103
01:06:03.540 --> 01:06:07.200
cue. Should the AI cue just put a box and

1104
01:06:07.260 --> 01:06:10.220
alert your attention visually, or should it give you the diagnosis?

1105
01:06:11.520 --> 01:06:12.240
On the right,

1106
01:06:13.840 --> 01:06:16.220
we're studying the timing of the AI cue.

1107
01:06:16.920 --> 01:06:18.160
At the top, you'll see

1108
01:06:19.320 --> 01:06:22.740
what we're doing in the PRISM mammography study, which is the

1109
01:06:22.800 --> 01:06:26.640
radiologist is given the AI information before they even

1110
01:06:26.700 --> 01:06:27.980
look at the exam.

1111
01:06:30.380 --> 01:06:33.360
That might be biasing them. There may be automation bias.

1112
01:06:33.460 --> 01:06:36.740
We don't know. At the bottom, I'm looking at delayed cue

1113
01:06:36.760 --> 01:06:40.340
presentation, in that clinician makes an

1114
01:06:40.400 --> 01:06:41.990
independent interpretation,

1115
01:06:43.120 --> 01:06:47.060
then they see the AI, and they can decide if they want to change their diagnosis.

1116
01:06:48.200 --> 01:06:51.420
In this study, we're also working with cognitive psychologists.

1117
01:06:51.540 --> 01:06:55.500
We're looking at eye tracking. What happens when there's different

1118
01:06:55.560 --> 01:06:56.700
types of cues?

1119
01:06:57.640 --> 01:07:00.479
How does that alter the time, et cetera?

1120
01:07:01.600 --> 01:07:05.180
So we're basically investigating real-world impact of AI

1121
01:07:05.880 --> 01:07:09.640
and how we clinicians are going to

1122
01:07:09.700 --> 01:07:11.700
interact with the AI

1123
01:07:11.840 --> 01:07:17.490
tools.In

1124
01:07:17.510 --> 01:07:17.890
summary,

1125
01:07:19.170 --> 01:07:20.330
I started describing

1126
01:07:21.570 --> 01:07:22.390
two domains

1127
01:07:23.310 --> 01:07:25.730
where I think we have challenges and we need to do better.

1128
01:07:26.010 --> 01:07:29.610
Risk prediction models, they work really good at the

1129
01:07:29.650 --> 01:07:31.590
population level, but

1130
01:07:33.090 --> 01:07:35.690
I'm seeing patients one-on-one. I want help.

1131
01:07:35.950 --> 01:07:37.140
I want them to do better

1132
01:07:38.430 --> 01:07:40.760
with my individual patient in the clinic.

1133
01:07:41.610 --> 01:07:45.040
Secondly, diagnostic accuracy. I've shown that it is

1134
01:07:45.190 --> 01:07:48.540
really hard, especially for those cases in the middle of the

1135
01:07:48.610 --> 01:07:49.770
diagnostic spectrum.

1136
01:07:50.570 --> 01:07:54.310
And I've also shown how we physicians are not always reproducible.

1137
01:07:54.470 --> 01:07:57.790
We may not give the same diagnosis if you give us six months

1138
01:07:59.950 --> 01:08:02.470
time period in between looking at the data.

1139
01:08:04.010 --> 01:08:04.430
Finally,

1140
01:08:06.670 --> 01:08:10.490
while AI tools hold great potential and I'm

1141
01:08:10.550 --> 01:08:11.270
optimistic,

1142
01:08:12.790 --> 01:08:16.130
they require rigorous evaluation.

1143
01:08:16.431 --> 01:08:18.610
We need to ensure that they're enhancing

1144
01:08:19.690 --> 01:08:23.490
and not disrupting the clinical care we're giving to patients.

1145
01:08:25.250 --> 01:08:25.650
Thank you.

1146
01:08:31.370 --> 01:08:35.300
Okay, I call all the speakers up to the stage, and we'll have a

1147
01:08:35.370 --> 01:08:38.370
panel discussion and take questions from the audience.

1148
01:08:43.410 --> 01:08:46.670
And there are microphones distributed in the aisles.

